<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-434-997  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 434 997.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC User  August 15 1990 n139 p12(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EMAP Business andamp; Computer Publications(England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Windows sales push Microsoft to (one-billion-pound) mark. (Windows3.0 sales make Microsoft the first PC software vendor to recordover one billion pounds sterling in sales)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (finance).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Product:   Microsoft Windows 3.0 (Graphical user interface) (salesstatistics).andO;Topic:     Software PublishersSalesFinancial AnalysisMarketing StrategyProfitGraphical User Interface.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Windows sales push Microsoft to 1bn pounds mark Microsoft become the first PCsoftware vendor to achieve global sales of 1 billion pounds.andP;  Sales ofWindows 3.0 since its May launch already exceed 500,000 copies, according toMicrosoft, and the company's application division surpassed Lotus in globalrevenue terms for the first time.andM;Global sales for the year ended 30 June 1990 reached $1.18 billion -- a 47per cent increase over 1989's $803.5 million.andP;  Net profits for the year wereup 64 per cent to $279.2 million.andM;Microsoft's UK managing director, David Svendsen, predicted that Microsoft'sglittering fortunes will continue due to a number of factors.andM;He said: &quot;Traditionally hardware is where the big bucks have been.andP;  Noweveryone agrees that software will soon account for the majority of value ina sale.andP;  Research shows that the typical Macintosh user has between five andseven applications on his machine whereas PC users typically have less thantwo.andP;  Windows 3.0 will bring the GUI into the PC mainstream and as a result,I believe PC users will follow Macintosh users and buy more applications.andO;Soon, more will be spent on software than hardware per PC.&quot;andM;&quot;Apart from OS/2, which has been disappointing, nearly everything is sellingwell,&quot; he added.andM;Svendsen promised that a full 32-bit implementation of OS/2 would be releasedwithin 12 months, but he saw little need for the cut-down version of OS/2,which IBM has suggested as a boost to OS/2's sales.andP;  &quot;There's little point ina version of OS/2 requiring, say, 2MB of memory when Windows 3.0 isavailable,&quot; he said.andM;Svendsen added that Microsoft has &quot;aspirations to come out with a databaseproduct for the PC,&quot; but he ruled out the launch of such a product for atleast 12 months.andP;  More immediately Microsoft is planning a major assault onthe networking market which Svendsen describes as undergoing &quot;explosivegrowth,&quot; see news, issue 138.andO;</TEXT></DOC>